[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Utilization of a new diagnostic tool in Small Claims Track, Fast Track and Multi-Track [bold](Complex) [bold]Whiplash cases.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]NeuroPAS Global (UK)[bold] L[bold]imi[bold]t[bold]e[bold]d[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Gary Cavazzi[bold]CFO/COO[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Dr Steve McVittie MFOM[bold]Consultant Occupational Physician [bold]Chief Medical Officer[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Consultation questions:[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Question 1: Do you agree that, in future, medical reports for whiplash injury claims should be supplied by independent medical panels, using a standard report form, and should be available equally to claimants, insurers, and (for contested claims) the courts?[bold]Yes
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Question 2; If not, how would you address the problems listed at paras. 35–39 above?[bold]N/A
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Question 3: Which model should be used for the independent medical panels – [bold]Accreditation, national call-off contract or some other variant?[bold]Accreditation of Independent medical practitioners (only if a scientifically sound objective medical tool is used to augment the diagnostic process, rather than only using subjective opinion). 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Question 4: Do you consider that an element of peer review should be built into every assessment, or only for a sample of assessments for audit purposes?[bold]Peer reviews should be used for a sample of assessments, but only if an augmented diagnostic process is used. If not, a second opinion would be needed for 100% of claims.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Question 6: Should the Small Claims track threshold be increased to £5,000 for RTA related whiplash claims, be increased to £5,000 for all RTA PI claims or not changed?[bold]The threshold should be raised to £5,000 for all RTA related to whiplash claims, but with a caveat that random medical checks being made. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Question 7: Will there be an impact on the RTA Protocol and could this be mitigated?[bold]Unknown
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Question 8: What more should the Government consider doing to reduce the cost of exaggerated and/or fraudulent whiplash claims?[bold]Use a scientifically sound objective medical tool is to augment the diagnostic process, and stop relying solely on subjective clinical opinion).
[normal]Question 9: Do you agree with the accompanying equality screening? If not, please explain why.[bold]Yes
[normal]Question 10: Can you identify ways in which the procedure under current arrangements impacts on people with protected characteristics? If so please provide evidence of impact.[bold]No, except that reactions to a whiplash experience can be influenced by gender, cultural or social factors. 
[normal]Question 11: Do you consider that the introduction of independent medical panels to assess whiplash injuries will impact on people with protected characteristics? If so, please give details.[bold]Not if suitable code of practice is encompassed with the accreditation process.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Question 12: Do you consider that an increase in the small claims limit for Whiplash/RTA personal injury claims from £1,000 to £5,000 will affect people with protected equality characteristics? If so, please give details.[bold]Not if suitable code of practice is encompassed with the accreditation process.
